an class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=cotopaxi@nuclearspace>cotopaxi</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 17<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/2/03 7:30:51 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=180.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Will it take money,science engineering,both to fix shuttle?</span><hr size=1> Well, I ain't no expert on space shuttle aerodynamics, but was there once a request to provide shuttle with a solid heat resistant sole (much like the sole of a shoe) under carriage in effect having two structures so you can change out the under carriage after each flight?<br>
<br>
And can't this detachable sole be better designed with blisters to direct and strengthen sensitive areas with upgraded compounds; rather than have the shuttle move around within its plasma bubble on re-entry ? <br>
<br>
I also read about literature that electrical pulses can create electromagnetic fields that mitigate the effects of plasma upon re-entry along the leading edges of the shuttle's nose and surrounding wing structure.<br>
I would think the people that study plasma dynamics could manipulate its effects that could have created the wreckage of shuttle Columbia flight STS-107.<br>
I guess this would cost more in terms of the physics and more money but isn't this natural in order to maybe fix problems that cause disasters? <br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nuclaeon>Nuclaeon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 112<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/2/03 8:54:35 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=180.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Will it take money,science engineering,both to fix shutt</span><hr size=1> First I think we need to actually find out what happened.  I personally feel the era of the shuttle should end.  It is a relic shell of 1980s technology partially integrated with more recent technology.  I think we can do better. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=cotopaxi@nuclearspace>cotopaxi</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 18<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/3/03 10:22:06 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=180.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Will it take money,science engineering,both to fix shuttle?</span><hr size=1> True...my feeling is tiles came off against a spacecraft going through a &quot;blow torch&quot;. If you take the possible problem the shuttle's under carriage should be a solid structure. Looking at bridge building to LEO...your right NASA should look at SSTO, Orbital spaceplane etc. Beyond LEO nuclear power must be used-no question. <br>
<br>
This means domestic public interest to do this which means an adequate budget not to mention other countries sharing the load in getting their people interested in space activities and participating directly. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tmayes1999>tmayes1999</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 228<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/3/03 12:26:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=180.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   What is wrong with the shuttle, and why it failed on 2-9-03.</span><hr size=1> The space shuttle orbiter has an alumnium air frame<br>
in order to make it lite weight. Lite weight is essential<br>
because the orbiter uses chemical propulsion instead<br>
of nuclear propulsion.Aluminium is a weak metal whose<br>
melting point is only around 600 C or so. Aluminium has an extreme vunerability to heat. Just a 100 C or so is enough<br>
 temperature  to fatally weaken  aluminium metal, and cause<br>
it to be distorted , or warped.The skin, and frame under the space shuttle heat shield is made of Aluminium metal.<br>
In your car it is also  an aluminium engine if it was made<br>
much  after 1980. In you car if the engines heats up to<br>
more then 100 C it will cause the aluminium head gasket<br>
of the engine to fail. This causes more heating still, and loss<br>
of compression in your cylinders. This is another Example<br>
of the shortcomings of aluminium metal.<br>
The Aluminium metal airframe, and skin of the space shuttle<br>
orbiter is why the damage to a few tiles from getting hit by <br>
some kevlar insultation from the fuel tank during launch destroyed the space shuttle during rentry and killed 7 people.<br>
The damaged tiles allowed the aluminium to get to hot, and<br>
thus become warped or distorted. At 12,500 miles an hour<br>
the tiles are effecively battered with an 18,000 to  12,500 mile per hour wind during reentry.The distortion of the frame caused failure of the glue that holds the tiles on in the heat shield. This caused the catastrophic failure of the heat shield<br>
and the distruction of the shuttle.<br>
If the shuttle had a titanium or steel frame, and skin it would not have been destroyed on reentry by a few damaged tiles.<br>
This would make the shuttle much heavier also. If you used<br>
nuclear propulsion instead of chemical propulsion on the shuttle this extra weight from a steel or titanium airframe would not be a problem..The shuuttle external tank is necessary to get into leo for the shuttle for mass ratio<br>
reasons. This mass ratio problem that results in the external<br>
tank results from the use of low specific impulse chemical<br>
rocketry.If nuclear propulsion were used , then you need<br>
only a 2.72 mass ratio to make leo. This can be achieved<br>
with an Ntr propulsion shuttle that is totaly made of steel,<br>
or titanium instead of aluminium. The shuttle would then be much smaller, much cheaper, much safer, more reliable,<br>
much stronger, much more  heat resistant , and much more likely to always survive rentry 100% undamaged if it were<br>
nuclear propelled, and made of steel or titanium instead of aluminium metal , and had no srbs , and no external tank.<br>
et el. A nuclear shuttle does not need any of this stuff<br>
to do its job..I personally would probably say  say give me Soyuz instead of the Shuttle every time   I go into orbit in a chemical rocket. If you give me a space shuttle it better be a nuclear one, made of steel, and tianium  or, otherwise I would always choose to ride soyuz with the russians,  instead of<br>
 the shuttle with our own people.<br>
Timothy J Mayes<br>
