 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=cotopaxi@nuclearspace>cotopaxi</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 20<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/4/03 12:03:10 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=180.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Tiles belong in a bathroom not on a winged LEO space vehicle</span><hr size=1> My bet is any winged vehicle has its advantage for serious cargo capacity servicing in entering any planet/moon with any atmosphere-bar none. <br>
<br>
The shuttle is a winged spacecraft and despite failure its basic science and physics are sound it just means that modifications need to take place to correct problems other than keeping junk off the heatshield.<br>
<br>
First,any winged vehicle should have a seamless<br>
undercarriage,solid heatshield that is a detachable 'Boot'.<br>
This for service, maintenance, inspection or change out. Less parts less problems.<br>
Second,the heatshield 'boot' would be equipped with the toughened upgraded heat resistant lightweight composite material in solid mold configuration rather than<br>
individual tiles. Yea, this is going to be tough to build because of it size but give some contractor/s out there the chance to assume the challenge.<br>
Third, the science of Plasma dynamics should be proactive in mitigating it effects on structure this again means giving the contractor/s involved in its study the chance to provide their service.<br>
