True... but a vehicle that can make a powered descent would not be subjected to such stresses as those encountered in a meteoric plunge through the atmosphere.  Although it sure would be nice to have both capabilities in a single vehicle, powered and glide descent, for insurance reasons... didn't the Buran have a couple of turbojets for 'go around' capability on landing strip approach? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=cotopaxi@nuclearspace>cotopaxi</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 21<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/4/03 1:17:24 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=180.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Tiles belong in a bathroom not on a winged LEO space vehicle</span><hr size=1> Yea, if I remember correctly the turbo jets mounted on on the tail of the pilot drone 'Buran' was just that, it was for flight dynamics testing, not as a feature of actual operation on final pilotless space launched drone test. The only other powered decent was Rototron? but this was abandoned. Really...unless your ET with anti-gravity subtle (powered) decent.This requiring tons of fuel/hardware making the situation worse for us humans. Entering any planet/moon in our universe that has any  atmosphere, you'll need to deal with its effect. It hard to do inspite of the false sense the public gets when we step on to an airliner, its a risk you take, but we do it anyway...same as driving car, riding bike etc.etc.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1949<br>