Did Buran use heat tile technology as well? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 813<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/4/03 10:19:19 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=180.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Buran </span><hr size=1> The Buran had 38,000 heat tiles and lost five of those on its maiden voyage according to <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://liftoff.msfc.nasa.gov/rsa/buran.html">this site.</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->  We should have taken a hint from the Soviets when they dumped their shuttle fleet.  According to the book &quot;The Soviet Drive to the Moon&quot; the only reason the Soviets built the Buran in the first place was because they feared the real purpose of the US shuttle was to be a weapon and they wanted to make sure they had a similiar &quot;weapon.&quot;  It's tragic considering that the Russian plans to build a small base on the Moon ultimately died because of their paranoia when they saw the Americans developing a shuttle.   <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A> at: 2/4/03 11:19:56 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1956<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/5/03 9:42:15 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=180.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/zaphod3.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Buran </span><hr size=1> But I like the fact that the Energia/Buran combo was more flexible... The Energia could be launched as a HLV minus the Buran... unlike the US S.T.S. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 827<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/5/03 1:53:12 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=180.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Buran </span><hr size=1> Even though I have to admit that I don't have much affection for the current crop of space shuttles, I would have liked to see the Soviets make use of their shuttles.  If the Burans though came anywhere near the price of maintenance that the US shuttle fleet does it might have ultimately put Russia out of space when the USSR ceased to exist.  It's good the Russians still had the tooling and infrastructure available to keep producing their undoubtedly cheaper Soyuz line.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1961<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/5/03 2:19:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=180.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/zaphod3.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Buran </span><hr size=1> I heard on NPR that a Soyuz takes 20 months to build at a cost of US $18 million... not sure if that includes the booster or not. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tmayes1999>tmayes1999</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 237<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/5/03 5:02:35 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=180.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Buran </span><hr size=1> 18,000,000 million dollars is the total price for 1<br>
