ad, anyone know? I think the shuttle is somewhat cheaper per pound than was the Saturn V, and the shuttle is certainly roomier. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1966<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/6/03 9:14:00 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=180.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/zaphod3.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Shuttle Capacity</span><hr size=1> A Saturn V placed the Skylab in LEO... Skylab weighed about 100 tons.<br>
